<p><b>Totalitarianism</b> (or <b>totalitarian rule</b>) is a concept used to describe <a href="/wiki/Political_systems" title="Political systems" class="mw-redirect">political systems</a> whereby a <a href="/wiki/Sovereign_state" title="Sovereign state">state</a> regulates nearly every aspect of public and private life. Totalitarian <a href="/wiki/Regimes" title="Regimes" class="mw-redirect">regimes</a> or movements maintain themselves in <a href="/wiki/Political_power" title="Political power">political power</a> by means of an official all-embracing <a href="/wiki/Ideology" title="Ideology">ideology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Propaganda" title="Propaganda">propaganda</a> disseminated through the state-controlled <a href="/wiki/Mass_media" title="Mass media">mass media</a>, <a href="/wiki/Single-party_state" title="Single-party state">a single party</a> that controls the state, <a href="/wiki/Personality_cult" title="Personality cult" class="mw-redirect">personality cults</a>, control over the <a href="/wiki/Economy" title="Economy">economy</a>, regulation and <a href="/wiki/Restriction" title="Restriction">restriction</a> of <a href="/wiki/Freedom_of_speech" title="Freedom of speech">free discussion and criticism</a>, the use of <a href="/wiki/Mass_surveillance" title="Mass surveillance">mass surveillance</a>, and widespread use of <a href="/wiki/State_terrorism" title="State terrorism">state terrorism</a>.</p>
